properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected this afternoon. Winds will rise to southwest 70 km/h gusting to 90 early this afternoon and will ease early in the evening. A cold front will sweep across the BC Peace River today. Gusty winds will rise through the morning, peaking in the afternoon. The strongest winds are expected to ease by the evening, however gusty westerly winds will likely continue through the night in the wake of the front. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential winter storm beginning Thursday. Total estimated snowfall: likely exceeding 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h or higher. Locations: Avalon Peninsula, Clarenville and vicinity and Bonavista Peninsula. Time span: Thursday afternoon into Friday. Remarks: A storm is expected to form south of Nova Scotia on Wednesday and track east of Newfoundland Thursday and Friday. Snow is expected to spread across Newfoundland Thursday afternoon, accompanied by strong winds and areas of blowing snow. Blizzard-like conditions are possible Thursday afternoon and night. Conditions will improve on Friday. There is still uncertainty regarding the track of this storm, which will have a significant impact on snowfall amounts. Should the storm pass further east, snowfall amounts will be much less, while if it tracks closer to the Avalon, higher accumulations will be expected. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for tonight. Snow squalls have developed this evening behind a cold front. Under these snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to heavy snow. These bands will shift with time over the region, thus limiting amounts in a given location. However, snowfall accumulations of up to 15 cm are expected in a few locales by Wednesday midday when the snow squalls taper to flurries. In addition, strong westerly winds gusting to 50 km/h will result in local blowing snow and may cause near-zero visibility at times. Motorists are advised to exercise caution or consider postponing travel. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Description: Strong winds with gusts near 100 km/h will subside overnight. ### High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. Snow will continue today in the wake of a frontal system moving onto the north coast. Additional snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm is expected today. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
